  "text": "The core Kafka Streams topology abstractions are defined in three key files:\n\n1. **Topology** (apache/kafka/streams/src/main/java/org/apache/kafka/streams/Topology.java) - This is a public class that provides a logical representation of a ProcessorTopology. It's a graph of sources, processors, and sinks that forms the DAG (directed acyclic graph) of processing nodes. The Topology class is the foundation for defining processing logic, which can then be passed into a KafkaStreams instance.\n\n2. **StreamsBuilder** (apache/kafka/streams/src/main/java/org/apache/kafka/streams/StreamsBuilder.java) - This is a public class that provides the high-level Kafka Streams DSL (Domain Specific Language) for specifying a Kafka Streams topology. It wraps an internal Topology instance and provides convenient builder methods for creating streams and tables, allowing developers to express their stream processing logic in a more intuitive way. The builder constructs a Topology and makes it available via the build() method.\n\n3. **KafkaStreams** (apache/kafka/streams/src/main/java/org/apache/kafka/streams/KafkaStreams.java) - This is a public class that implements AutoCloseable and serves as the runtime for executing a topology. It's a Kafka client that allows for performing continuous computation on input coming from one or more input topics and sends output to zero, one, or more output topics. A KafkaStreams instance takes a Topology (or the result of StreamsBuilder.build()) and a Properties configuration, then manages the execution of the stream processing application across one or more threads, coordinating with other instances in a distributed setting."
}

